Conditions in Java:-->

			There are four condition statements in java.
				if
				else
				if else
				switch
				
				
			Conditions allow perticual statements to execute based on 
			decision.
			
			
			Logical conditions from mathematics.
				
					=> Less Than     					a < b
					=> Less Than or equal to 			a <=b
					=> GreaterThan						a > b
					=> Greaterthan or equal to			a >=b
					=> Equal to							a ==b
					=> NotEquals						a!=b
					
					
					
if codition:-->
		if statement to specify a block of java code to be executed
		when condition is true. [If accept only boolean value]
		
		
		
		Syntax:-->
		
				if(condition)
				{
						//StateMent to executed on true condition
				}
				
				
		Example:-->
		
				
				if(20 > 19 )
				{
					System.out.println("Statement1");
					System.out.println("Statement2");
				}
				
				
		Example:-->
				int a=10;
				int b=20;
				
				if(a < b)
				{
					System.out.println("True condition");
				}
==========================================================================>
else Condition:-->
		Else statement to specify a block of code to be executed when condition
		is return false.	
		
		int age=17;
		if(age > 18)
		{
			System.out.print("true condition");
		}
		else
		{
			System.out.print("false condition");
		}	
		
===========================================================================
else if:-->
		else if statement to specify a new condition to execute when
		first codition failed.
		
		
		if(condition)
		{
				//First condition
		}
		else if(codnition2)
		{
				//Second condition
		}
		else
		{
				//Final condition to execute
		}
		
		
		
		Example:-->
		
		String  name="sunil";
		String  email="anil@email.com";
		String  mobile="9030248855;
		
		
		if(name.equals("anil"))
		{
				System.out.prinln("name is approved");
		}
		else if(email.equals("sunil@email.com")
		{
				System.out.prinln("email is approved")
		}
		else if(mobile.equals("9030248855")
		{
				System.out.prinln("mobile is approved")
		}
		else
		{
				System.out.println("Authentication failed")
		}
		
====================================================================>
SwitchCase:-->
	Switch case work same as else if condition only difference is
	it execute required block of code directly insted of checking 
	each and every statement.	
		
				
		Syntax:-->
		
				Switch(Expression)
				{
					case x:
							//Code to be execute for case x
					break;
					
					
					case y:
							//Code to be execute for case y
					break;
					
					default:
							//if any case not macthing it execute default block
					break;
	
				}
				
				
				
			
				
				
				
				
				
		
		
		
		
		